The promise toast `toast.promise()` is super handy but sometimes I have a long-running task that I want the user to be able to cancel, which could be achieved using a [AbortController](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/AbortController) and [AbortSignal](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/AbortSignal).

Whilst I could try to manually inject a `AbortController` manually, there's no elegant way to handle the success/error state since the promise will either error or succeed.

If the library were to offer a native `AbortSignal` then it could elegantly handle the aborted state. For example if the type of `toast.promise` is

```diff
declare const toast: ((message: titleT, data?: ExternalToast) => string | number) & {
-   promise = (promise: Promise<ToastData> | () => Promise<ToastData>, ...)
+   promise = (promise: Promise<ToastData> | (signal: AbortSignal) => Promise<ToastData>, ...)
```

and the type of `PromiseData` has a `cancel` (like the [existing cancel option](https://sonner.emilkowal.ski/toast#cancel)) and `aborted` message to display when it's aborted

```diff
type PromiseData<ToastData = any> = PromiseExternalToast & {
    loading?: string | React.ReactNode;
    success?: PromiseTResult<ToastData> | PromiseTExtendedResult<ToastData>;
    error?: PromiseTResult | PromiseTExtendedResult;
+   cancel?: string | React.ReactNode;
+   aborted?: PromiseTResult | PromiseTExtendedResult;
    description?: PromiseTResult;
    finally?: () => void | Promise<void>;
};
```

Then I could use it like

```tsx
toast.promise(
  async (signal) => {
    await fetch("https://...", { signal });
  },
  {
    loading: 'Downloading...',
    success: `Downloaded`,
    error: `Error downloading`,
    cancel: 'Cancel',
    aborted: 'Download cancelled'
  }
);
```

Passing id directly with potentially undefined value, for example as `{ id: data?.id }`, results in inconsistency between returned id and the one actually assigned to the toast, resulting in impossibility to update toast.

```
function toast(message: Message, params?: ExternalToast) {
    return sonner.custom(() => <div>Toast</div>, { id: params?.id })
}
```

If no params passed, or id is not passed through params, data within `custom` would be as { id: undefined }

```
custom = (jsx: (id: number | string) => React.ReactElement, data?: ExternalToast) => {
    const id = data?.id || toastsCounter++;
    this.create({ jsx: jsx(id), id, ...data });
    return id;
};
```

In the implementation first id is calculated correctly resulting in `const id = data?.id || toastsCounter++;` returning numeric id.

However, later in code `this.create({ jsx: jsx(id), id, ...data });` spreaded data is overwriting newly created id with undefined value, resulting in creating yet another id inside `this.create` function.
`const id = typeof data?.id === 'number' || data.id?.length > 0 ? data.id : toastsCounter++;` 

This leads to one id being returned, while another id being assigned to the toast, removing possibility to update toast by id.

Problem potentially should be solved if overwrite data.id with calculated one
`this.create({ jsx: jsx(id), ...data, id });`

### Problem
Some web-apps have critical messages that need to be seen, or a message that may be toasted during a page navigation or refresh. This PR adds message durability so certain toasts can be restored after a page refresh.

### Summary
- Add `persistent` option to toast configuration
- Implement localStorage-based persistence with SSR safety
- Normalize sonner id upon restoration with counter synchronization moved into class
- staggered animation for toast restoration
- customizable `storageKey` prop to Toaster component

### Usage
Basic:
```tsx
toast('Persistent Toast', { persistent: true })} 
```
Works with evolving toasts, will update persistence if the toast updates:
```tsx
toast.promise(
  new Promise((resolve) => {
    setTimeout(() => {
      resolve({ name: 'Sonner' });
    }, 2000);
  }),
  {
    loading: 'Loading...',
    success: (data: any) => ({
      message: `${data.name} toast has been added`,
      description: 'Custom description for the Success state',
    }),
    description: 'Global description',
    persistent: true,
    closeButton: true,
  },
)
```

### Restoration Compatibility
All types of toasts can be used with the persistent property. But, Each toast is stringified and then parsed when restored so obviously any functions or timeouts become disconnected.

### Demo
https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/dc867d05-629b-4248-b8e8-995a3a2143d8

Example

```ts
import { useEffect } from 'react'
import { createRoot } from 'react-dom/client'
import { toast, Toaster } from 'sonner'

function App() {
  useEffect(() => {
    toast.success('Hello')
  }, [])
  return (
    <>
      <Toaster
        position="top-center"
        container={
          document.querySelector('#root')!.shadowRoot?.querySelector('body')!
        }
      />
    </>
  )
}

const host = document.getElementById('root')!
const shadow = host.attachShadow({ mode: 'open' })
const container = document.createElement('body')
shadow.appendChild(container)
createRoot(container).render(<App />)
```

