`toast.promise()` method takes 2 arguments 1 is **Promise** so, the promise will be anything. and the second is data I mean (`PromiseData`).

The promise data type is
- **loading** (which will accept a string or ReactNode)
- **success** (which will accept a string or ReactNode or your response data) don't worry I'll share some examples in the below section.
- **error** (which will also accept string or ReactNode or your response error) remember this `error` only works when an error occurs.

```js
// create a promise using new Promise
   const promise = new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
      setTimeout(() => {
        resolve("resolve");
        // reject("reject");
     }, 5000);
  });
  const clickHandler = async () => {
    // toast promise
    toast.promise(promise, {
      loading: "promise loading...",
      //This data will be your response data
      /**
       * success: (data) => {
       *  return `promise success. ${data.name}`;
       * },
       */
      success: "promise success",
      error: "promise error!",
      finally: () => {
        // promise is finally done then execute this method
      },
    });

    //You can handle like this way. when clickHandler triggers then make loading and if success then toast.succes also for error toast.error
    toast.loading("loading");
    promise
      .then((data) => {
        toast.success(`promise success. ${data}`);
      })
      .catch((e) => {
        toast.error("error" + e);
      })
      .finally(() => {
        console.log("finally");
      });

    // new way with try, catch block (same as a promise)
    toast.loading("loading");
    try {
      const res = await promise;
      toast.success(`success ${res}`);
    } catch (err) {
      toast.error(`success ${err}`);
    }
  };
```

