I was able to resolve the spinner issue by doing this:

```tsx
const toastId = toast.loading('...');

toast.custom(
  (t) => {
    return (...)
  },
  { id: toastId, icon: null }
);
```

But the `duration` issue means the custom toast won't ever dismiss itself, even if `duration` is set.

`toast()` itself will return an id when you execute it. I have a similar function where I'm doing:
```typescript
const id = toast(..., {duration: Infinity})
if (error) { 
  return toast.dismiss(id) 
}
if (success) {
  toast(..., {id, duration: 4000})
```
Greatly simplified but you should get the idea.

There is a bug in the custom toast function that's incrementing the internal id twice if you pass a nullish id. Usually this happens if you let your custom toast have an optional id passed

```ts
function Toast(props: {
   id?: string | number
}) {
  return toast.custom(..., {
    id: props.id, // <- this breaks as id can be  undefined
  });
}
```

```ts
function Toast(props: {
   id?: string | number
}) {
  const toastProps = {};
  if (props.id) {
    toastProps.id = props.id
  }

  return toast.custom(..., toastProps); // <- doesn't break because id is passed only if it has a value
}
```
